# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: editable-text-buffer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] In computer science, a **circular buffer**, **circular queue**, **cyclic buffer** or **ring buffer** is a data structure that uses a single, fixed-size buffer as if it were connected end-to-end.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] This structure lends itself easily to buffering data streams.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] There were early circular buffer implementations in hardware.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] A circular buffer first starts out empty and has a set length.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] If two elements are removed, the two oldest values inside of the circular buffer would be removed.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Circular buffers use FIFO (*first in, first out*) logic.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] In the example, 1 & 2 were the first to enter the circular buffer, they are the first to be removed, leaving 3 inside of the buffer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] When elements get removed, only the read-pointer moves to the next element.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Removed elements are still in the buffer, waiting to get overwritten by new elements.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] A property of the circular buffer is that when it is full and a subsequent write is performed, then it starts overwriting the oldest data.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Alternatively, the routines that manage the buffer could prevent overwriting the data and return an error or raise an exception.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Whether or not data is overwritten is up to the semantics of the buffer routines or the application using the circular buffer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] The useful property of a circular buffer is that it does not need to have its elements shuffled around when one is consumed.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] (If a non-circular buffer were used then it would be necessary to shift all elements when one is consumed.) In other words, the circular buffer is well-suited as a FIFO (*first in, first out*) buffer while a standard, non-circular buffer is well suited as a LIFO (*last in, first out*) buffer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Circular buffering makes a good implementation strategy for a queue that has fixed maximum size.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Should a maximum size be adopted for a queue, then a circular buffer is a completely ideal implementation; all queue operations are constant time.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] However, expanding a circular buffer requires shifting memory, which is comparatively costly.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] For arbitrarily expanding queues, a linked list approach may be preferred instead.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] In some situations, an overwriting circular buffer can be used, e.g. in multimedia.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] If the buffer is used as the bounded buffer in the producer–consumer problem then it is probably desired for the producer (e.g., an audio generator) to overwrite old data if the consumer (e.g., the sound card) is unable to momentarily keep up.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Also, the LZ77 family of lossless data compression algorithms operates on the assumption that strings seen more recently in a data stream are more likely to occur soon in the stream.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Implementations store the most recent data in a circular buffer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] In the beginning the indexes end and start are set to 0.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] The circular buffer write operation writes an element to the end index position and the end index is incremented to the next buffer position.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] The circular buffer read operation reads an element from the start index position and the start index is incremented to the next buffer position.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] The start and end indexes alone are not enough to distinguish between buffer full or empty state while also utilizing all buffer slots, but can be if the buffer only has a maximum in-use size of Length − 1.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] In this case, the buffer is empty if the start and end indexes are equal and full when the in-use size is Length − 1.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Another solution is to have another integer count that is incremented at a write operation and decremented at a read operation.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Then checking for emptiness means testing count equals 0 and checking for fullness means testing count equals Length.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] The following source code is a C implementation together with a minimal test.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Function put() puts an item in the buffer, function get() gets an item from the buffer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] A circular-buffer implementation may be optimized by mapping the underlying buffer to two contiguous regions of virtual memory.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] When the read offset is advanced into the second virtual-memory region, both offsets—read and write—are decremented by the length of the underlying buffer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Perhaps the most common version of the circular buffer uses 8-bit bytes as elements.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Some implementations of the circular buffer use fixed-length elements that are bigger than 8-bit bytes—16-bit integers for audio buffers, 53-byte ATM cells for telecom buffers, etc.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Each item is contiguous and has the correct data alignment, so software reading and writing these values can be faster than software that handles non-contiguous and non-aligned values.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Ping-pong buffering can be considered a very specialized circular buffer with exactly two large fixed-length elements.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] The *bip buffer* (bipartite buffer) is very similar to a circular buffer, except it always returns contiguous blocks which can be variable length.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] This offers nearly all the efficiency advantages of a circular buffer while maintaining the ability for the buffer to be used in APIs that only accept contiguous blocks.
[src:editable-text-buffer/circular-buffer] Fixed-sized compressed circular buffers use an alternative indexing strategy based on elementary number theory to maintain a fixed-sized compressed representation of the entire data sequence.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] In computer science, a **finger tree** is a purely functional data structure that can be used to efficiently implement other functional data structures.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] A finger tree gives amortized constant time access to the "fingers" (leaves) of the tree, which is where data is stored, and concatenation and splitting logarithmic time in the size of the smaller piece.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] It also stores in each internal node the result of applying some associative operation to its descendants.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] This "summary" data stored in the internal nodes can be used to provide the functionality of data structures other than trees.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Ralf Hinze and Ross Paterson state a finger tree is a functional representation of persistent sequences that can access the ends in amortized constant time.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Concatenation and splitting can be done in logarithmic time in the size of the smaller piece.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] The structure can also be made into a general purpose data structure by defining the split operation in a general form, allowing it to act as a sequence, priority queue, search tree, or priority search queue, among other varieties of abstract data types.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] A *finger* is a point where one can access *part* of a data structure; in imperative languages, this is called a pointer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] In a finger tree, the fingers are structures that point to the ends of a sequence, or the leaf nodes.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] The fingers are added on to the original tree to allow for constant time access to fingers.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] In the images shown below, the fingers are the lines reaching out of the spine to the nodes.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] A finger tree is composed of different *layers* which can be identified by the nodes along its *spine*.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] The spine of a tree can be thought of as the trunk in the same way trees have leaves and a root.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Though finger trees are often shown with the spine and branches coming off the sides, there are actually two nodes on the spine at each level that have been paired to make this central spine.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] The *prefix* is on the left of the spine, while the *suffix* is on the right.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Each of those nodes has a link to the next level of the spine until they reach the root.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] The first level of the tree contains only values, the leaf nodes of the tree, and is of depth 0.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] The closer to the root, the deeper the subtrees of the original tree (the tree before it was a finger tree) the nodes points to.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] In this way, working down the tree is going from the leaves to the root of the tree, which is the opposite of the typical tree data structure.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] To get this nice and unusual structure, we have to make sure the original tree has a uniform depth.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] To ensure that the depth is uniform, when declaring the node object, it must be parameterized by the type of the child.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] The nodes on the spine of depth 1 and above point to trees, and with this parameterization they can be represented by the nested nodes.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] We will start this process with a balanced 2–3 tree.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] For the finger tree to work, all the leaf nodes need to also be level.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] A finger is "a structure providing efficient access to nodes of a tree near a distinguished location." To make a finger tree we need to put fingers to the right and left ends of the tree and transform it like a zipper.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] This gives us that constant amortized time access to the ends of a sequence.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] To transform, start with the balanced 2–3 tree.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Take the leftmost and rightmost internal nodes of the tree and pull them up so the rest of the tree dangles between them as shown in the image to the right.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Combines the spines to make a standard 2–3 finger tree.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] The digits in the examples shown are the nodes with letters.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Each list is divided by the prefix or suffix of each node on the spine.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] In a transformed 2–3 tree it seems that the digit lists at the top level can have a length of two or three with the lower levels only having length of one or two.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] In order for some application of finger trees to run so efficiently, finger trees allow between one and four subtrees on each level.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] And so on the image, the top level has elements of type *a*, the next has elements of type *Node a* because the node in between the spine and leaves, and this would go on meaning in general that the *n*th level of the tree has elements of type $Node^{n}$ *a*, or 2–3 trees of depth n.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] This means a sequence of *n* elements is represented by a tree of depth Θ(log *n*).
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Even better, an element *d* places from the nearest end is stored at a depth of Θ(log d) in the tree.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] This process can also be done with other trees, like the 2–3–4 tree at right.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] This helps to see that the Digits are actually the annotations which were inside the tree, and each digit is conceptually associated with a subtree that may be empty.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Finger trees also make efficient deques.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Whether the structure is persistent or not, all operations take Θ(1) amortized time.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] The analysis can be compared to Okasaki's implicit deques, the only difference being that the FingerTree type stores Nodes instead of pairs.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Finger trees can be used to build other trees.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] For example, a priority queue can be implemented by labeling the internal nodes by the minimum priority of its children in the tree, or an indexed list/array can be implemented with a labeling of nodes by the count of the leaves in their children.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Other applications are random-access sequences, described below, ordered sequences, and interval trees.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Finger trees can provide amortized O(1) pushing, reversing, popping, O(log n) append and split; and can be adapted to be indexed or ordered sequences.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] And like all functional data structures, it is inherently persistent; that is, older versions of the tree are always preserved.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Finger trees can efficiently implement random-access sequences.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] This should support fast positional operations including accessing the *n*th element and splitting a sequence at a certain position.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] To do this, we annotate the finger tree with sizes.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] The new type is needed because the type is the carrier of different monoids.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Another new type is still needed for the elements in the sequence, shown below.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] These lines of code show that instance works a base case for measuring the sizes and the elements are of size one.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] The use of **newtype**s doesn't cause a run-time penalty in Haskell because in a library, the *Size* and *Elem* types would be hidden from the user with wrapper functions.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] With these changes, the length of a sequence can now be computed in constant time.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Finger trees were first published in 1977 by Leonidas J.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Finger trees have since been used in the Haskell core libraries (in the implementation of *Data.Sequence*), and an implementation in OCaml exists which was derived from a proven-correct Rocq implementation.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] There is also a verified implementation in Isabelle (proof assistant) from which programs in Haskell and other (functional) languages can be generated.
[src:editable-text-buffer/finger-tree] Finger trees can be implemented with or without lazy evaluation, but laziness allows for simpler implementations.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] A **gap buffer** in computer science is a dynamic array that allows efficient insertion and deletion operations clustered near the same location.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] Gap buffers are especially common in text editors, where most changes to the text occur at or near the current location of the cursor.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] The text is stored in a large buffer in two contiguous segments, with a gap between them for inserting new text.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] Moving the cursor involves copying text from one side of the gap to the other (sometimes copying is delayed until the next operation that changes the text).
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] Insertion adds new text at the end of the first segment; deletion deletes it.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] Text in a gap buffer is represented as two strings, which take very little extra space and which can be searched and displayed very quickly, compared to more sophisticated data structures such as linked lists.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] However, operations at different locations in the text and ones that fill the gap (requiring a new gap to be created) may require copying most of the text, which is especially inefficient for large files.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] The use of gap buffers is based on the assumption that such recopying occurs rarely enough that its cost can be amortized over the more common cheap operations.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] This makes the gap buffer a simpler alternative to the rope for use in text editors such as Emacs.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] Below are some examples of operations with buffer gaps.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] The gap is represented by the empty space between the square brackets.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] This representation is a bit misleading: in a typical implementation, the endpoints of the gap are tracked using pointers or array indices, and the contents of the gap are ignored; this allows, for example, deletions to be done by adjusting a pointer without changing the text in the buffer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/gap-buffer] User moves the cursor before "started"; system moves "started " from the first buffer to the second buffer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] In computing, a **piece table** is a data structure typically used to represent a text document while it is edited in a text editor.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] Initially a reference (or "span") to the whole of the original file is created, which represents the as yet unchanged file.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] Subsequent inserts and deletes replace a span by combinations of one, two, or three references to sections of either the original document or to a buffer holding inserted text.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] Typically the text of the original document is held in one immutable block, and the text of each subsequent insert is stored in new immutable blocks.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] Because even deleted text is still included in the piece table, this makes multi-level or unlimited undo easier to implement with a piece table than with alternative data structures such as a gap buffer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] This data structure was invented by J Strother Moore.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] For this description, we use buffer as the immutable block to hold the contents.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] To retrieve the *i*-th character of the PTD, the appropriate entry in a piece table is read.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] A real implementation of a piece table will not include a PTD indices ("pieced-together document") column due to the column containing information that can be deduced from the piece table's start index, length, and row position, but it is shown above for educational purposes.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] The piece table's ordering of rows implicitly describes the ordering of characters to use from the available buffers.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] I.e., the first row of the piece table (e.g., <Add,0,6>) describes the first sequence of characters in the PTD (e.g., PTD indices 0–5).
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] The second row of the piece table (e.g., <Original,0,5>) describes the sequence of characters from a possibly different buffer that will immediately follow the characters chosen from the first sequence (e.g., PTD indices 6–10).
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] In the above example, the piece table indicates that the PTD will have 6 + 5 + 6 + 9 = 26 characters.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] To get the (character) value `Index(15)`, we first find the entry (row) in the piece table that corresponds to the PTD index 15.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] The first entry describes characters in PTD indices 0 to 5, the second entry PTD indices 6 to 10, and the 3rd entry PTD indices 11–16.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] Since the 3rd entry of the piece table corresponds to PTD index 15 (11 ≤ 15 ≤ 16), the 3rd entry is retrieved.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] The piece table's 3rd entry instructs the program to look for the characters in the "*add file*" buffer, starting at index 17 in that buffer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] The relative index in that entry is PTD_SoughtIndex − PTD_StartIndexOfEntry = 15 − 11 = 4, which is added to the start position of the entry in the buffer to obtain the index of the letter: 4 + 17 = 21.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] The value of `Index(15)` is the 21st character of the "add file" buffer, which is the character "o".
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] Several text editors use an in-RAM piece table internally, including Bravo, Abiword, Atom and Visual Studio Code.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] The "fast save" feature in some versions of Microsoft Word uses a piece table for the on-disk file format.
[src:editable-text-buffer/piece-table] The on-disk representation of text files in the Oberon System uses a **piece chain** technique that allows pieces of one document to point to text stored in some other document, similar to transclusion.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] In computer programming, a **rope**, or **cord**, is a data structure composed of smaller strings that is used to efficiently store and manipulate longer strings or entire texts.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] For example, a text editing program may use a rope to represent the text being edited, so that operations such as insertion, deletion, and random access can be done efficiently.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] A rope is a type of binary tree where each leaf (end node) holds a string of manageable size and length (also known as a *weight*), and each node further up the tree holds the sum of the lengths of all the leaves in its left subtree.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] A node with two children thus divides the whole string into two parts: the left subtree stores the first part of the string, the right subtree stores the second part of the string, and a node's weight is the length of the first part.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] For rope operations, the strings stored in nodes are assumed to be constant immutable objects in the typical nondestructive case, allowing for some copy-on-write behavior.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] Leaf nodes are usually implemented as basic fixed-length strings with a reference count attached for deallocation when no longer needed, although other garbage collection methods can be used as well.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] In the following definitions, *N* is the length of the rope, that is, the weight of the root node.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] These examples are defined in the Java programming language.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] Repeat the procedure for p's right subtree.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] and rebuild the tree from the bottom-up.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] This operation can be done by a `Split()` and two `Concat()` operations.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] For example, to find the character at `i=10` in Figure 2.1 shown on the right, start at the root node (A), find that 22 is greater than 10 and there is a left child, so go to the left child (B).
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] 9 is less than 10, so subtract 9 from 10 (leaving `i=1`) and go to the right child (D).
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] Then because 6 is greater than 1 and there's a left child, go to the left child (G).
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] 2 is greater than 1 and there's a left child, so go to the left child again (J).
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] Finally 2 is greater than 1 but there is no left child, so the character at index 1 of the short string "na" (ie "n") is the answer.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] A concatenation can be performed simply by creating a new root node with left = S1 and right = S2, which is constant time.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] The weight of the parent node is set to the length of the left child *S*1, which would take ⁠ $O(\log N)$ ⁠ time, if the tree is balanced.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] As most rope operations require balanced trees, the tree may need to be re-balanced after concatenation.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] The split point is in the middle of a string.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] The second case reduces to the first by splitting the string at the split point to create two new leaf nodes, then creating a new node that is the parent of the two component strings.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] For example, to split the 22-character rope pictured in Figure 2.3 into two equal component ropes of length 11, query the 12th character to locate the node *K* at the bottom level.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] Go to the parent of *G* and subtract the weight of *K* from the weight of *D*.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] Travel up the tree and remove any right links to subtrees covering characters past position 11, subtracting the weight of *K* from their parent nodes (only node *D* and *A*, in this case).
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] Finally, build up the newly orphaned nodes *K* and *H* by concatenating them and creating a new parent *P* with weight equal to the length of the left node *K*.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] As most rope operations require balanced trees, the tree may need to be re-balanced after splitting.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] This operation can be done by two `Split()` and one `Concat()` operation.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] First, split the rope in three, divided by *i*-th and *i+j*-th character respectively, which extracts the string to remove in a separate node.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] To report the string *Ci*, …, *C**i* + *j* − 1, find the node *u* that contains *Ci* and `weight(u) >= j`, and then traverse *T* starting at node *u*.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] Output *Ci*, …, *C**i* + *j* − 1 by doing an in-order traversal of *T* starting at node *u*.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] This table compares the *algorithmic* traits of string and rope implementations, not their *raw speed*.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] Array-based strings have smaller overhead, so (for example) concatenation and split operations are faster on small datasets.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] However, when array-based strings are used for longer strings, time complexity and memory use for inserting and deleting characters becomes unacceptably large.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] In contrast, a rope data structure has stable performance regardless of data size.
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] Further, the space complexity for ropes and arrays are both O(n).
[src:editable-text-buffer/rope-data-structure] In summary, ropes are preferable when the data is large and modified often.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] A **zipper** is a technique of representing an aggregate data structure so that it is convenient for writing programs that traverse the structure arbitrarily and update its contents, especially in purely functional programming languages.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The zipper was described by Gérard Huet in 1997.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] It includes and generalizes the gap buffer technique sometimes used with arrays.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The zipper technique is general in the sense that it can be adapted to lists, trees, and other recursively defined data structures.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] Such modified data structures are usually referred to as "a tree with zipper" or "a list with zipper" to emphasize that the structure is conceptually a tree or list, while the zipper is a detail of the implementation.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] A layperson's explanation for a tree with zipper would be an ordinary computer file system with operations to go to parent (often `cd ..`), and to go downwards (`cd subdirectory`).
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The zipper is the pointer to the current path.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] Behind the scenes, zippers are efficient when making (functional) changes to a data structure, where a new, slightly changed, data structure is returned from an edit operation (instead of making a change in the current data structure).
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] Many common data structures in computer science can be expressed as the structure generated by a few primitive constructor operations or observer operations.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] A list such as `[1, 2, 3]` is therefore the declaration `Cons(1, Cons(2, Cons(3, Empty)))`.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] It is possible to describe the location in such a list as the number of steps from the front of the list to the target location.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] More formally, a location in the list is the number of `Cons` operations required to reconstruct the whole list from that particular location.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] For example, in `Cons(1, Cons(2, Cons( X, Cons(4, Empty))))` a `Cons(2, L)` and a `Cons(1, L)` operation would be required to reconstruct the list relative to position X otherwise known as `Cons( X, Cons(4, Empty))`.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] This recording together with the location is called a zipped representation of the list or a list-zipper.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] To be clear, a location in the list is not just the number of `Cons` operations, but also all of the other information about those `Cons`; in this case, the values that must be reconnected.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] Here, these values may be conveniently represented in a separate list in the order of application from the target location.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] Specifically, from the context of "3" in the list `[1, 2, 3, 4]`, a recording (commonly referred to as a 'path') could be represented as `[2, 1]` where `Cons(2, L)` is applied followed by `(Cons 1, L)` to reconstitute the original list starting from `[3, 4]`.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] A list-zipper always represents the entire data structure.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] However, this information is from the perspective of a specific location within that data structure.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] Consequently, a list-zipper is a pair consisting of both the location as a context or starting point, and a recording or path that permits reconstruction from that starting location.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The list may then be efficiently reconstructed: `[1, 2, 10, 4]` or other locations traversed to.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] With the list represented this way, it is easy to define relatively efficient operations on immutable data structures such as Lists and Trees at arbitrary locations.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] In particular, applying the zipper transform to a tree makes it easy to insert or remove values at any particular location in the tree.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The type of a zipper's contexts can be constructed via an operation on the original type that is closely related to the derivative of calculus through decategorification.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The recursive types that zippers are formed from can be viewed as the least fixed point of a unary type constructor of kind $*\rightarrow *$ .
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] For example, with a higher-order type constructor ${\text{lfp}}:(*\rightarrow *)\rightarrow *$ that constructs the least fixed point of its argument, an unlabeled binary tree can be represented as ${\text{lfp}}(T\mapsto T^{2}+1)$ and an unlabeled list may take the form ${\text{lfp}}(T\mapsto T+1)$ .
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] Here, the notation of exponentiation, multiplication, and addition correspond to function types, product types, and sum types respectively, whilst the natural numbers label the finite types; in this way, the type constructors resemble polynomial functions.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The derivative of a type constructor can therefore be formed through this syntactic analogy, and the zipper of the type constructor is the derivative paired with its element type.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] In this way, the derivative can be viewed as a zipper with a hole in it, where a value could be placed.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] Consider the type of singly-linked lists.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The list data structure can be defined as $L(X)=1+X\times L(X)$ .
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] That is, L is a type constructor which takes an element type X and produces the type of lists of that element type.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The two addends correspond to the two data constructors for a list.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The `Nil` data constructor, a sentinel node that holds no data, is represented by the unit type 1 , and the `Cons` constructor is represented as a product of the head element X and the tail L of the list.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] Under this representation, the derivative $L'$ of L in terms of X is $L'(X)=L(X)+X\times L'(X)$ .
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] That is, if we have a zipper-with-a-hole for a list, then either (I) the hole is the very first element, and the rest of the list is an ordinary (non-zipper) list $L(X)$ , or (II) the first element is present ( X ) and the hole is somewhere else further down the tail of the list ( $L'(X)$ ).
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] Then the formal type of a zipper for a linked list is $X\times L'(X)$ , or $X\times (L(X)+X\times L'(X))$ .
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] Put another way, a zipper for a linked list consists of an element in that list and instructions on where to put it in a partially-built list.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] For another example, consider the recursive data structure of a binary tree with nodes that are either sentinel nodes of type 1 or which are leaves containing a value of some type X .
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] We can represent this type algebraically as $T(X)=1+X\times T^{2}(X)$ .
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The derivative in terms of X is $T'(X)=T^{2}(X)+2\times X\times T(X)\times T'(X)$ .
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] In the latter case, the Boolean type 2 indicates which branch (left or right) contains the hole, and the zipper contains a value for the root, a $T(X)$ for the complete branch, and a $T'(X)$ for the branch that's missing a value of type X .
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The complete type of a zipper for this binary tree structure, then, is $X\times T'(X)$ , or $X\times (T^{2}(X)+2\times X\times T(X)\times T'(X))$ .
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] In general, a zipper consists of two parts: a collection of contexts for the current node and each of its ancestors up until the root node, and the value that the current node contains.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The zipper is often used where there is some concept of focus or a cursor used to navigate around in some set of data, since its semantics reflect that of moving around but in a functional non-destructive manner.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] In a non-purely-functional programming language, it may be more convenient to simply traverse the original data structure and modify it in place (perhaps after deep cloning it, to avoid affecting other code that might hold a reference to it).
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] The generic zipper is a technique to achieve the same goal as the conventional zipper by capturing the state of the traversal in a continuation while visiting each node.
[src:editable-text-buffer/zipper-data-structure] However, the generic zipper involves inversion of control, so some uses of it require a state machine (or equivalent) to keep track of what to do next.
